1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
 So the title, as you know, is "Give to God what is God's", "Ceasar what is Caesar's", "To the Church what is Church's", and "To me what is mine".

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:18,000
 First of all, why I deal with that stuff, not just today for this conference, but also in general.

3
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:29,000
 Just because I'm fascinated with that relationship between Church and State, that doesn't mean at all that I understand the problem properly.

4
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:34,000
 So don't expect too much of me.

5
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:36,000
 I'm just fascinated.

6
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:39,000
 And I think that it's unavoidable.

7
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:52,000
 We cannot avoid the question who is right in that sense in understanding of proper relationship between Emperor and God or State and Church and so forth.

8
00:00:52,000 --> 00:01:00,000
 But you can also be on the right side without proper understanding of the problem.

9
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:04,000
 So I think that my knowledge about that is very poor.

10
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:08,000
 It's bigger than average student, but it's very poor in general.

11
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:15,000
 But I'm trying to be thought-provoking and to understand something.

12
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:30,000
 And I'm consoled with the words of big Jacques Maritain, who said that he researched about this problem for 25 years.

13
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:40,000
 So if he had to research about that problem for 25 years, it could take much more for me.

14
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:42,000
 I'm not sure about you.

15
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:56,000
 Another brief note is that we have heard a lot today from the historical and theological point of view.

16
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,000
 It seems to me that it's just a basic thing.

17
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:00,000
 I like to.

18
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:05,000
 I love philosophy because it seems to me that it always deals with the very basic things.

19
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:13,000
 It doesn't mean that it's easy to deal with basic things, but I like to deal with very basic things.

20
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:30,000
 So the difference between history, philosophy, and inside philosophy, ethics, and then specifically political philosophy, from my point of view, is that history deals much more with facts.

21
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:34,000
 And philosophy deals also with facts.

22
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:37,000
 It takes in account also historical facts.

23
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:46,000
 It's impossible to philosophize without historical perspective, but it's also possible to philosophize without any historical fact.

24
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:56,000
 But philosophy deals much more with principles, not so much with facts, especially historical facts.

25
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:04,000
 Inside the philosophy, ethics is a field in philosophy or branch, if you want.

26
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:19,000
 Maybe it's better to say field in philosophy, which deals with a question, together with political philosophy, and I understand political philosophy as a branch of ethics, not independent tree.

27
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:23,000
 So political philosophy is a branch of ethics.

28
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:30,000
 And the philosophy of ethics, they both deal with questions, what should be.

29
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:35,000
 Not just what it is, what could be, but also what should be.

30
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:40,000
 It's not a question for history in a narrow sense.

31
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:43,000
 So facts and principles, we take both.

32
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:47,000
 But I'm much more interested in principles, not so much here.

33
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:59,000
 That's why I have esteemed colleagues from history department, from theology department, and other departments, because I'm much more interested in principles.

34
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:00,000
 Very basic.

35
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:02,000
 Another basic thing.

36
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:19,000
 And it seems to me that it's proper to say that we as persons, as individuals and persons, and we as a humankind, willing or not, knowing that or not, we are searching for something like that.

37
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:27,000
 Peace, freedom, safety, and we can call altogether, let's say, happiness.

38
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:29,000
 Peace, freedom, safety.

39
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:40,000
 So, the part of that peace, freedom, safety is, of course, justice and some order.

40
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:48,000
 It seems to me that it's proper to say that peace is a consequence of some order.

41
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:53,000
 You can call that also justice, but order, I choose the word order.

42
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:56,000
 Peace is a consequence of some order.

43
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:58,000
 And what is order?

44
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:09,000
 That now, already a little children, order is when all things are at proper place.

45
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:23,000
 So we are trying for centuries, even for millennia now, to put these things, God, Caesar, state, man, to proper place.

46
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:28,000
 And still, we are not much successful.

47
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:30,000
 It's my point of view.

48
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:33,000
 I think you agree.

49
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:38,000
 So, peace is a consequence of order.

50
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:44,000
 And order is a consequence of the fact that things are in its proper place.

51
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:58,000
 Second thing, also basic and very, very simple, is that our life as individuals and as humankind is sort of a conquest of freedom.

52
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:01,000
 So we are not born free in that sense.

53
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:04,000
 We have to conquer the freedom.

54
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:17,000
 That doesn't mean that we are slaves, but for a little baby, we, in that sense, cannot say that she or he is free yet.

55
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:22,000
 She or he has to conquer his or her freedom.

56
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:37,000
 So I see, that's also historical perspective, I see the history as a sort of a very big human walk to conquer the freedom.

57
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:54,000
 For example, when we see the time of Christ when he was on earth, when he said that famous sentence, give or render to Caesar's, to Caesar what is Caesar's and to God what is God's.

58
00:06:54,000 --> 00:07:13,000
 In fact, that was the beginning of liberation of religion from the iron hug of empire or state or emperor, however you want.

59
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:20,000
 So, when we see the history of the church, we have many religious orders.

60
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:31,000
 Because, it seems to me, I'm a philosopher, not a theologian, so I'm a philosopher inside the Catholic Church, it's true, but I think as a philosopher, not as a theologian.

61
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:48,000
 It seems to me that we can say, and it's true, one of things, one of facts, that religious orders, among other things, are established because of searching for more freedom inside the church.

62
00:07:48,000 --> 00:08:00,000
 And it seems to me that all history of the church, similarly as the history in general, is a conquest of freedom of every single person.

63
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:07,000
 So, these are questions from my summary you have in your booklets.

64
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:11,000
 I will not read all of them, just a few of them, just to remember.

65
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:15,000
 So, what does the principle, give to Caesar's and so forth, mean today?

66
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:21,000
 Who is Caesar? Who is God? Who has the mandate to interpret this principle?

67
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:26,000
 Me, you, state, church, pope, who?

68
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:28,000
 What about the church in this context?

69
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:35,000
 I mean, usually I mean Catholic church, but you can take any other church if you want.

70
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:38,000
 Does the relationship between church and state imply equality?

71
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:40,000
 It's a very important question.

72
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:45,000
 Or does one side have primacy?

73
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:49,000
 So, is it egalitarian or it's hierarchical vision?

74
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:55,000
 Because it seems to me that we have a lot of problems because of misunderstanding that question.

75
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:59,000
 Separation of powers, very simply.

76
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:06,000
 Are they like this or like that in a sort of scheme?

77
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:09,000
 Are God and the church one and the same?

78
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:13,000
 Is there anything that is not God's, that doesn't belong to God?

79
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:18,000
 Does giving to the church mean the same as giving to God?

80
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:22,000
 And what about me and my conscience in this whole story?

81
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:24,000
 What belongs to me, if anything?

82
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:27,000
 So, these are my questions.

83
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:34,000
 If you expect direct answers, I have to disappoint you because I don't have direct answers.

84
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:38,000
 Maybe a few of them, but maybe indirect answers.

85
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:47,000
 So, I follow, just to present what I am following, I follow this guy on the right side of the screen.

86
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:49,000
 It's Jacques Maritain.

87
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:55,000
 He follows St. Thomas Aquinas, of course, and both of them follow Aristotle.

88
00:09:55,000 --> 00:10:05,000
 So, that's the line which I am also following in my research.

89
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:17,000
 Distinguish to unite is a sort of a, I'm not sure is a proper word in English, sort of a maxima, sort of a light motive of a whole Maritain's philosophy.

90
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:30,000
 So, we have many of these sentences and you can recognize immediately when you say something, for example, it's I love or like Plato, but I like more the truth.

91
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:32,000
 You immediately know it's Aristotle.

92
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:33,000
 And much more sentences.

93
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:46,000
 So, if you want to recognize Maritain's philosophy, you have to know that Distinguish to Unite is his light motive of his whole philosophy.

94
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:53,000
 These two books primarily I recommend if you are not yet familiar with his philosophy.

95
00:10:53,000 --> 00:11:02,000
 This, on the right side, is the Elder One, Primacy of the Spiritual, or on the things that are not Caesar's.

96
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:04,000
 It is written in the '30s.

97
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:16,000
 I think that the first edition, it was precisely in the 1930s, after the problems with L'Action Francaise in France and papal condemnation of L'Action Francaise.

98
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:19,000
 It was the Pope Pius XI.

99
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:24,000
 And this, on the left side, is a very famous book of Jacques Maritain.

100
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:27,000
 One of the most popular books is Men and State.

101
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:28,000
 It's much younger.

102
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:29,000
 It's from the '50s.

103
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:36,000
 So, these two books I recommend for those who are not familiar yet and for this topic.

104
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:45,000
 So, on the line of that Distinguished to Unite, I propose a vision of history as a process of discernment.

105
00:11:45,000 --> 00:12:00,000
 So, we, as persons, as individuals, and as mankind, even as a church, throughout the history, we are discerning more and more.

106
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:02,000
 We are seeing more and more.

107
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:13,000
 So, what we see today about this, that probably principle, yes, but in details, we see much more today, as a church or as a humankind,

108
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:17,000
 more and more than 500 years ago or 1,000 years ago or 2,000 years ago.

109
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:22,000
 Similar, like in individual life, we discern things.

110
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:26,000
 So, discernment is very often enough.

111
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:30,000
 That's very nice and good news.

112
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:37,000
 So, it's not entirely clear in this story what belongs to whom.

113
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:44,000
 So, it's easy to say, give to Caesars or render to Caesars what is Caesars, but what precisely does that mean?

114
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:48,000
 So, Christ didn't give that answer.

115
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:55,000
 What does it mean that we have to deal with that question for our own, as individuals and as community.

116
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:57,000
 So, it's not entirely clear.

117
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:02,000
 And it seems to me that it will not be clear for a long time in front of us.

118
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:03,000
 I don't know how much.

119
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:08,000
 First of all, it's a political statement in some sense.

120
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:14,000
 Of course, everything what comes out from Jesus' mouth, it's theological.

121
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:19,000
 It's eternal truth from a religious or perspective of faith.

122
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:23,000
 But, it's also political sentence.

123
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:27,000
 It's very dangerous political sentence.

124
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:34,000
 Because, in some sense, for example, for Jews, maybe it's not so much scandalous.

125
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:40,000
 But, for Romans, it could be scandalous because that means that Caesar is not God.

126
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:42,000
 So, it's first discernment.

127
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:49,000
 So, because, as Professor just before me mentioned, we have very different images of God.

128
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:54,000
 So, it can be, and they are often, idols, not real God.

129
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:57,000
 Even a religious person can have such sense.

130
00:13:57,000 --> 00:13:59,000
 And, what about non-religious person?

131
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:07,000
 So, Romans, they all have, they all had some sort of a picture of God.

132
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:14,000
 When Jesus said, "Give or render to Caesar what is Caesar's, and to God what is God's,"

133
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:18,000
 that is distinguishing Caesar from God.

134
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:21,000
 But, an important thing is a question.

135
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:27,000
 Maybe we don't realize that it's a very serious question.

136
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:29,000
 What is the relationship between God and Caesar?

137
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:31,000
 Maybe they are equal.

138
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:34,000
 Maybe God is below the Caesar.

139
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:36,000
 What does Jesus want to say?

140
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:43,000
 So, we have to try to enter the shoes of Romans and Jews from Christ's time.

141
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:51,000
 So, it's pretty clear for us that when Jesus says that, that God is above Caesar.

142
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:53,000
 There is hierarchy.

143
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:59,000
 There is primacy of something or somebody.

144
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:03,000
 There is no equality between God and Caesar.

145
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:09,000
 So, you have to give what is God's to God and Caesar's what is Caesar's.

146
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:11,000
 But, there is primacy.

147
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:12,000
 There is hierarchy.

148
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:16,000
 It seems to me that it's not clear today when we talk about church and state.

149
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:22,000
 So, hierarchy and primacy are very important concepts in this sense.

150
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:23,000
 We, our vision.

151
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:24,000
 We, our vision.

152
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:26,000
 Christian, specifically Catholic vision.

153
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:33,000
 My vision is hierarchical vision of reality in total and especially in this sense.

154
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:35,000
 Hierarchy and primacy.

155
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:38,000
 Maritaine also had that book I showed you.

156
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:41,000
 So, the primacy of the spiritual.

157
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:43,000
 The primacy of the spiritual was the title.

158
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:48,000
 And then, the subtitle on the things that are not Caesar's.

159
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:54,000
 So, this is a sort of a scheme for school children.

160
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:57,000
 God, church, state, persons.

161
00:15:57,000 --> 00:15:58,000
 We could see.

162
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:01,000
 I'm not sure which scheme is proper.

163
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:03,000
 You could help me if you want.

164
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:05,000
 So, God is above the church.

165
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:06,000
 Church is above the state.

166
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:08,000
 State maybe is above the persons.

167
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:12,000
 But, maybe the scheme is like that.

168
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:15,000
 We change the positions of state and persons.

169
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:19,000
 Because persons are created by God.

170
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:21,000
 And state is not created by God.

171
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:23,000
 State is created by man.

172
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:28,000
 So, if the state is creation.

173
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:33,000
 And even not creation of God, but creation of man.

174
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:38,000
 Then, maybe it's not proper to think that state is something above.

175
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:41,000
 In that hierarchical vision of the reality.

176
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:44,000
 But something below the persons.

177
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:45,000
 And then, comes the question.

178
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:49,000
 What about the relationship between church and persons?

179
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:51,000
 So, I'm repeating again.

180
00:16:51,000 --> 00:16:52,000
 I'm not theologian.

181
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:56,000
 I respect doctrine of the Catholic Church.

182
00:16:56,000 --> 00:16:58,000
 I'm a philosopher inside the Catholic Church.

183
00:16:58,000 --> 00:16:59,000
 But my question is.

184
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:04,000
 Maybe the proper hierarchical scheme is like this.

185
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:09,000
 It's for sure that men and the church.

186
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:11,000
 From the Christian perspective.

187
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:14,000
 Are created by God.

188
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:17,000
 So, church is not creation of man.

189
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:19,000
 But, the state is clear.

190
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:22,000
 The state doesn't exist without man.

191
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:24,000
 So, it's man creation.

192
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:29,000
 But, persons and church are both created by God.

193
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:30,000
 What is much important?

194
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:31,000
 Much more important.

195
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:33,000
 What is more important?

196
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:35,000
 Church or persons?

197
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:37,000
 Maybe a stupid question.

198
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:38,000
 But still.

199
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:41,000
 It seems to me that it's very important to think about that.

200
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:43,000
 So, I'm not sure.

201
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:49,000
 Is this proper scheme of that hierarchy of this or this one?

202
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:54,000
 We are persons in better position in that hierarchy.

203
00:17:54,000 --> 00:17:57,000
 In a higher position than the church.

204
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:00,000
 Even though the church is also created by God.

205
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:04,000
 And we say that the church is a mystical body of Christ.

206
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:06,000
 Who is son of God.

207
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:08,000
 So, he is God.

208
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:15,000
 Then comes the very important notion of conscience.

209
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:18,000
 Maritain wrote a lot of this stuff.

210
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:19,000
 So, what about conscience?

211
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:22,000
 Because conscience could be in conflict.

212
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:25,000
 Either with state or emperor.

213
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:30,000
 But, also with church authority.

214
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:32,000
 What about the freedom of conscience?

215
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:39,000
 It seems to me that it's very important to remember the slide about history as a process of discernment.

216
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:46,000
 Because we as Christians, and specifically as Catholics inside the Catholic Church.

217
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:58,000
 We also, inside the church, learned a lot about the problems of conscience and freedom of conscience.

218
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:04,000
 That means that we didn't know enough 1,000 years ago.

219
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:07,000
 Even we don't know enough today.

220
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:11,000
 So, it's a question of discerning still.

221
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:21,000
 So, if Jesus says, for example, Shabbat is for the sake of man.

222
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:27,000
 And Shabbat is also created by God, in some sense.

223
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:30,000
 So, it's God's creation.

224
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:32,000
 It's not established by man.

225
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:34,000
 It's established by God.

226
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:37,000
 It is for the sake of man.

227
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:41,000
 Could the same be said for the church?

228
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:44,000
 Church is for the sake of man.

229
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:48,000
 So, man is much more important than Shabbat.

230
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:57,000
 Could we say the same thing for the relationship between man and the church?

231
00:19:57,000 --> 00:20:03,000
 So, when everything is in order, it means that everything is in its place.

232
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:04,000
 The consequence is peace.

233
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:07,000
 I'm just remembering what I said earlier.

234
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:14,000
 So, it seems to me that all this process is for the sake of liberation of every man.

235
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:32,000
 So, not just of Jews in that time or after Jesus of church towards empire or emperor or today or in Middle Ages, whatever, towards state or kingdom, whatever.

236
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:34,000
 But liberation of every man.

237
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:44,000
 So, it's a sort of a process of atomization, but it's a controversial notion, but individualization or personalization of that thing.

238
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:55,000
 So, liberation of every man started maybe with a sentence, give to Caesar's what is Caesar's and to God what is God's.

239
00:20:55,000 --> 00:20:57,000
 Liberation of every man.

240
00:20:57,000 --> 00:21:06,000
 So, it seems to me also this, that we are not aware enough of the freedoms we talk about.

241
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:09,000
 When we talk about the freedom is connected with economy, for example.

242
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:22,000
 I'm not an expert in economy, but I know that in economy, when you have, for example, that big difference between capitalism and socialism,

243
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:26,000
 You have that concept of zero-sum-gain.

244
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:37,000
 So, the cake has a, has a sort of a, the cake is like it is.

245
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:41,000
 So, it's a big so-and-so.

246
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:50,000
 And we have to, we have to, we have to give to everybody how much is possible.

247
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:51,000
 That is zero-sum-gain.

248
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:54,000
 There is no possibility to enlarge the cake.

249
00:21:54,000 --> 00:22:08,000
 Capitalistic, for example, view in that sense is, in that sense is that the, the, the, the, the limitations of cake are not final.

250
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:18,000
 That, that wealth, growth, that, that, that we can enlarge our wealth.

251
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:23,000
 And that's the main difference between capitalism and socialism.

252
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:31,000
 And in that sense, when we talk about the freedom, it seems to me that we often talk in the sense that it's zero-sum-gain.

253
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:35,000
 If you have more freedom, that means that I will have less.

254
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:44,000
 If church has more freedom, that could mean that state will have less freedom.

255
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:50,000
 But I'm not proposing capitalistic view, of course, as a, as a solution of this problem.

256
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:53,000
 But it's inspiration for me to think about the freedom.

257
00:22:53,000 --> 00:23:01,000
 So, we can think, think about freedom as something, what can be enlarged for everybody.

258
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:05,000
 I have, I can have more freedom, and you can have more freedom.

259
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:07,000
 And church can have more freedom.

260
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:10,000
 And academia can have more, can have more freedom.

261
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:12,000
 And media can have more freedom.

262
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:14,000
 Everybody can have more freedom.

263
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:17,000
 So, and it's a, so-called connected vessels.

264
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:24,000
 When grows my freedom, that could mean that your freedom is also growing.

265
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:34,000
 And that, it seems to me, is often a source of a misunderstanding when we talk about the, the freedom of church, or freedom of state, or relationship between church and state.

266
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:44,000
 So, it seems to me that conquest of freedom, I already mentioned, it seems to me that we, today, have more freedom than ever in every aspect of life.

267
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:46,000
 We can discuss three days about that.

268
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:50,000
 But it seems to me that it's, it's true that we have more and more freedoms.

269
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:54,000
 But it's also true that the threat to our freedoms is bigger and bigger.

270
00:23:54,000 --> 00:23:58,000
 So, that's, I think that it's very much confusing.

271
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:00,000
 So, the threat is always bigger and bigger.

272
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:02,000
 How much time I have still?

273
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:05,000
 Very little, okay.

274
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:09,000
 I'm, I'm, so, in the end, everything, I'm concluding.

275
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:11,000
 Everything, in some sense, belongs to God.

276
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:19,000
 So, it's, it seems to me that it could be one of, of precise answers to my, one of my questions.

277
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:25,000
 I said that I will not give direct answers, but it could be one of direct answers.

278
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:27,000
 Everything, in some sense, belongs to God.

279
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:33,000
 It's impossible, especially, especially for a believer to think about something that does not belong to God.

280
00:24:33,000 --> 00:24:40,000
 But, everything should be given or rendered to God in order He wanted.

281
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:44,000
 So, that's, in my view, it's very important perspective.

282
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:56,000
 He wants that we understand properly the hierarchy of the creation and that everything is rendered to Him in that order.

283
00:24:56,000 --> 00:25:03,000
 When we don't understand properly that order, then we have this order and then we don't have peace.

284
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:08,000
 So, everything should be given to God, but in the order He wanted.

285
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:15,000
 And to man, also one, we could say, direct answers.

286
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:16,000
 What belongs to me?

287
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:18,000
 What belongs to man?

288
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:21,000
 At least, I can conclude one thing.

289
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:22,000
 At least.

290
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:25,000
 Freedom of conscience, of course, I mentioned that.

291
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:35,000
 But, to man belongs the right to have them, church and state in our, in our times, cooperate for His sake.

292
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:42,000
 So, it seems to me that it's clear that church is above as a spiritual realm.

293
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:47,000
 It's above, it's hierarchically above the state.

294
00:25:47,000 --> 00:25:49,000
 But, it's also for the sake of man.

295
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:57,000
 So, to man belongs the right to have them, church and state cooperate for his sake, for man's sake.

296
00:25:57,000 --> 00:26:09,000
 And it seems to me that fine-tuning is a magic word, in some sense, because nobody, in my view, knows precisely what does it mean.

297
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:10,000
 What does it mean?

298
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:18,000
 We know the principle and we, through fine-tuning, are searching for the proper positions of that.

299
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:25,000
 But, I propose hierarchy, hierarchical vision of God, person, church and state.

300
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:31,000
 And, to man belongs the right to have them, church and state cooperate for the sake of man.

301
00:26:31,000 --> 00:26:36,000
 And, in that relationship, church is above the state.

302
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:39,000
 And, this is the creation word for thank you.

303
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:40,000
 Hvala.

